title: yf-21
body:
A [[mecha]] from the [[MACROSS]] franchise. It first appeared in the [[Macross Plus]] OVA from 1994.

The [b]YF-21 Omega One[/b] is the first prototype of the [[VF-22]] [[variable fighter]]. This experimental advanced mecha was developed by the company [i]General Galaxy[/i] to be used by the [[U.N. Spacy]]. A test pilot for the YF-21 was [[Guld Goa Bowman]].

Fighter mode features include extreme high speed and maneuverability inside an atmosphere as well as a new mini [[pin-point barrier system]] adapted for variable fighter use.

The [[battroid]] mode of this unit strongly resembles the design of the old Quimeliquola [[Queadluun-Rau]] [[Zentradi]] [[power armor]] and also uses that [[alien]] mecha's original inertia vector control system and short range energy [[arm cannon]]s besides the standard [[gunpod]].

In [[real life]] it was designed by [[Kawamori Shouji]] (external fuselage design) and [[Miyatake Kazutaka]] ([[cockpit]] design) in the [[1990s_(style)|90s]]. [spoilers]The mind control system of the mecha was inspired by the one used in the [[Mig-31 Firefox]] jet from the movie [[firefox_(movie)|Firefox]].[spoilers]

title: walther_p38
body:
A 9×19mm semi-automatic [b][[handgun]][/b] that was developed by Carl [[Walther]] GmbH for [[Wehrmacht]] service at the beginning of [[World War II]], introduced in 1939. It was intended to replace the costly and primitive [[Luger P08]]. The [b]Walther P38[/b] is recognizable by its short, open-top slide that exposes the barrel and a rounded trigger guard. The mechanism itself influenced many modern handguns, such as the Beretta 92.

This tag also apply to some post-WWII variants such as the West German Walther P1 and South African Walther P4.

title: afrika_korps
body:
Also known as the [b]German Africa Corps[/b] or by its [[germany|German]] name, [i]Deutsches Afrikakorps[/i] (DAK), it was the German expeditionary force in [[Africa]] during the North African Campaign in [[World War II]]. First sent as a holding force to shore up the [[italy|Italian]] defense of their African colonies, the formation fought on in Africa from March 1941 until its surrender in May 1943.

The unit's best known commander was Field Marshal [[Erwin Rommel]].

title: crosier
body:
[i]A [[priest]]'s staff.[/i]

The real-life crosier (also spelled [i]crozier[/i]) is a stylized, often ornately-decorated staff that is a symbol of the governing office of a high-ranking [[Christianity|Christian]] priest. This staff generally comes in three forms: [b]hooked[/b], in the shape of a shepherd's crook (curled off to one side); [b]tau[/b], in the shape of a T with downwards-curving arms topped by a small [[cross]]; and [b]serpentine[/b], with a pair of sculptured serpents or dragons curled back to face each other in an upwards-facing U with a small cross between them. 

The [[fantasy]] version of the crosier tends to resemble a bastardized version of one (or several) of the above, with a small sphere or circular symmetrical  "shepherd's crook" bisected or topped by a large cross (the overall profile will often resemble a [[Celtic cross]]). Some versions may just be a large cross mounted on the end of a staff (with the whole staff resembling a [[Latin cross]], like the [[Pope]]'s [i]ferula[/i]). Another common fantasy variant has a scepter-like head topped off with a small cross.

[[Priest]]s and fantasy [[priestess]]es are often depicted holding a crosier. Some may instead be depicted wielding a generic [[mage staff]]; such examples should not be tagged crosier.

h4. Notable examples
* [[Arch bishop (ragnarok online)|]] ([[Ragnarok Online]])
* [[Pope_(ragnarok_online)|The Pope]] ([[Ragnarok Online]])
* [[Martha_(fate)|]] ([[Fate (series)]])
* [[Victorious_(azur lane)|]] ([[Azur Lane]])
** Wields a golden crosier tipped with a sun cross, surmounted with a ship's bell.
* [[Fan la Norne]] ([[Xenoblade Chronicles 2]])

h4. Tag usage notes
* Tag crosier for the priest's staff described above—both the real versions and the fantasy variants.
** As a general rule, any fantasy staff that appears vaguely [[christianity|Christian]]-like (i.e. festooned with crosses and Christian motifs) will also tend to qualify.
* Avoid tagging crosier for 'generic' looking staves that may be better off tagged [[staff]] or [[mage staff]].
** Fantasy [[priest]]([[priestess|ess]])es are sometimes depicted holding a 'generic' crystal or gem-tipped staff without any religious trappings, one that would not look out of place being wielded by any other magic user. These examples should be tagged [[mage staff]] and not crosier.
** Fire Emblem characters belonging to the priest or cleric class lines tend to just wield generic [[mage staff|mage staves]] because of [[Nintendo]] being allergic towards the depiction of crosses and other religious iconography.
* [b]Do not[/b] tag [[shakujou]] (i.e. Buddhist staves) with crosier.
* The [[Pope]]'s staff is a Papal ferula, but this can be tagged with crosier for now.

h4. See also
* [[Priest]]
* [[Priestess]]
* [[Mage staff]]
* [[Shakujou]] [tn]Buddhist equivalent, topped with multiple metal rings.[/tn]

h4. External links
* "Wikipedia: Crosier":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crosier]
* "Wikipedia: Papal Ferula":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Papal_ferula] 
** The [[Pope]]'s staff. Technically different, but currently tagged as same (because fantasy [[Priest]]s also tend to carry a similar staff).

title: another_eden
body:
[B]Another Eden: The Cat Beyond Time and Space[/B] is a JRPG developed by Wright Flyer Studios (WFS). The story involves time travel as well as other science fiction and fantasy elements. The game is written by Kato Masato and the main theme is composed by Mitsuda Yasunori, both of whom previously worked on [[Chrono Trigger]]. There are a number of references to the [i]Chrono[/i] series in the game. 

Another Eden is available on Android, iOS, and will be ported to Nintendo Switch in the future. The game is a single-player adventure that users may play at their own pace: all story content is permanent with no time limit, and the game lacks stamina timers. All main characters and many additional characters are free, unlocked as players progress. Other extra characters may be unlocked through an optional gacha system, the only form of monetization in the free-to-play game. Another Eden was first released in Japan on 2017 April 12. The global release began rolling out to other countries on 2019 January 28.

title: railway_gun
body:
A railway gun, also called a railroad gun, is a large [[artillery]] piece, often surplus naval ordnance, mounted on, transported by, and fired from a specially designed railway wagon. Many countries have built railway guns, but the best known are the large Krupp-built pieces used by Germany in [[World War I]] and [[World War II]]. Smaller guns were often part of an [[armored train]].

The film tells the story of [[Alex Rogan]] (played by Lance Guest), an idealisitic young man and gifted [[video game]]r [spoiler]recruited by an [[alien]] [[star_league|defense force]] to fight in an interstellar war due to his superior gaming skills.[/spoiler]

The movie also features Robert Preston (as [[Centauri]], his final role in a theatrical film), Dan O'Herlihy, Catherine Mary Stewart (as [[Maggie Gordon]]), Norman Snow, and Kay E. Kuter.

It has the capability to transform into three different modes: [b]Crusader[/b] (fighter), [b]Cross Fighter[/b] (heavy combat helicopter), and [b]Cosmo Sniper[/b] (humanoid).

"Marine Day (海の日, Umi no Hi), also known as 'Ocean Day' or 'Sea Day', is a public holiday in Japan usually celebrated on the third Monday in July. The purpose of the holiday is to give thanks for the ocean's bounty and to consider the importance of the ocean to Japan as a maritime nation. Many people take advantage of the holiday and summer weather to take a beach trip. Other ocean-related festivities are observed as well."

title: ehoumaki
body:
[b]Ehoumaki[/b] (恵方巻き, lit. "[[ehou|Lucky-Direction]] [[Makizushi]]") refers to the custom in the Kansai region of eating a [i]futomaki[/i] (a type of [[sushi]]) on the evening of [[Setsubun]] (February 3rd) while facing "Ehou" (the lucky direction that changes according to the year) or to the [[makizushi]] itself. Much like [[Valentine]]'s Day chocolate, it is almost a man-made custom spread by promotional activities of concerned bodies for reasons purely related to profit and sales.

In the 1970s, it spread through the Kansai region thanks to [[nori (seaweed)|nori]] distributors/wholesalers and [[sushi]] shops, and in the 2000s, it spread throughout Japan thanks to the [[convenience store]] industry. In other words, this custom is very new to places outside of Kansai.

title: sunday_silence_(racehorse)
body:
Sunday Silence (1986-2002) is a successful American racehorse and winner of two of the American Triple Crown in 1989. The horse, however, is better known as the leading sire in Japan for 13 years, including 5 years [i]posthumously[/i]. Many of his numerous offspring and descendants became successful racehorses themselves and several became popular sires and broodmares in their own right, especially [[Deep Impact (racehorse)|]] (2002 - 2019), one of his most successful offspring and successor as a long-streaking leading sire (11 years and counting). His influence is so pervasive to the point that nowadays, almost all racehorses in Japan racing at the highest level and aren't foreign-bred are direct descendants of Sunday Silence.

In the context of [i][[Umamusume]][/i], he is the RL sire or ancestor of a significant portion of the horse girls, especially the youngest in RL. Whenever he is portrayed as a horse girl, he usually takes the form of a [[look-alike]] of [[Manhattan Cafe (umamusume)|]] (or being just portrayed [i]by[/i] Manhattan Cafe) due to the original horse being said to be the spitting image of his sire, to the point of being able to stand-in as Sunday Silence in a TV movie about him and his Japanese owner, Yoshida Zen'ya.

title: t'au
body:
A faction from [[warhammer 40k|Warhammer 40,000]], characterized by their blue-skinned, humanoid forms and extensive use of [[mecha]]. The T'au would go from a primitive species to a spacefaring civilization capable of standing against the might of the [[imperium of man|Imperium]] in only a few millenia, driven by a philosophy they call the "Greater Good". Nominally a lighter faction within the grim darkness of the far future, the T'au have forged alliances with a number of other species, such as the reptillian Kroot and the insectoid Vespids, and have even recruited a number of human defectors from the Imperium. Beneath that, however, their ruling caste, the Ethereals, have kept their people ignorant of the dangers of the wider galaxy and may have sinister intentions for their civilization.

Nicknamed the "Weaboo Space Communists" by Imperial players as their designs appear to be heavily based on Japanese science fiction media and their ideology of the "Greater Good" is seen as collectivist enough to be compared/equated to communism, tongue-in-cheek or not.

title: intellivision
body:
The [b]Intellivision[/b] is an American home [[game console]] released by "Mattel":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mattel Electronics in 1979. 

The name Intellivision is a portmanteau of "Intelligent [[Television]]". Development of the console began in 1977, the same year as the introduction of its main competitor, the Atari 2600.
 
From 1980 to 1983 over 3 million Intellivision units were sold. In 1984 Mattel sold the Intellivision business to a former Mattel Electronics executive and investors that would become INTV Corporation. ROM [[game cartridge]]s development started in 1978 and continued until 1990 when the Intellivision was discontinued. 

In 2009, video game website IGN named the Intellivision the No. 14 greatest video game console of all time. It remained Mattel's only video game console until the release of the [[HyperScan]] in 2006.

title: the_metamorphosis

[b]The Metamorphosis[/b], also known simply as [b]Metamorphosis[/b] (German: [b]Die Verwandlung[/b]) is a [[fantasy]] novella written by "Franz Kafka":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Franz_Kafka which was first published in 1915. 

One of Kafka's best-known works, Metamorphosis tells the story of young deserting and unemployed salesman [[Gregor Samsa]], who due to lack of money lives with his parents and wakes one morning to find himself inexplicably transformed into a huge insect (German: [i]ungeheueres Ungeziefer[/i], lit. "monstrous vermin") and subsequently struggles to adjust to this new condition. 

The novella has been widely discussed among literary critics, with differing interpretations being offered. In popular culture and adaptations of the novella, the insect is commonly depicted as a [[cockroach]].

body:
[b]Sword Art Online Alternative: Gun Gale Online[/b] is a light novel spin-off series of [[Sword Art Online]] written by Shigusawa Keiichi, with supervision by Kawahara Reki, and illustrated by [[Kuroboshi Kouhaku]].  An anime adaptation aired Spring 2018 and a second season was announced in July of 2023.

The series is about Kohiruimaki Karen, a young college student who has a complex about her height of 183 cm (~72 in).  Enticed by the idea of being able to be someone else through a game avatar, Karen gets into Virtual Reality Massively Multiplayer Online Role Play Games (VRMMORPGs) wanting to be someone with a shorter stature.  She starts with ALfheim Online (ALO) using the name LLENN, but finds that the randomly assigned game avatar is too tall.  Advised by one of her friends, Karen transfers her account to various other games in the hopes of receiving a random avatar to her liking. She eventually settles on Gun Gale Online (GGO), as her randomly assigned avatar is a "chibi" with a height of 150 cm (~59 in).  The story starts after Karen becomes friends with an online player named Pitohui, who gets Karen to participate in a team-based tournament called Squad Jam.

title: chevrolet_camaro
body:
The Chevrolet Camaro is a mid-size American automobile manufactured by Chevrolet, classified as a pony car. 
It first went on sale on September 29, 1966, for the 1967 model year and was designed as a competing model to the Ford Mustang. 
The Camaro shared its platform and major components with the Firebird, produced by General Motors' Pontiac division that was also introduced for 1967.
Four distinct generations of the Camaro were developed before production ended in 2002. The nameplate was revived on a concept car that evolved into the fifth-generation Camaro; production started on March 16, 2009.

"Wikipedia Article":[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chevrolet_Camaro]

title: mouth_guard
body: A mouth guard is a shaped piece of plastic or rubber used to protect the teeth and gums from injury during contact sports activity, such as [[ice hockey|hockey]] or [[American football]]. Another kind of mouth guard, also called a sleep guard or bite guard, is used while sleeping to prevent the grinding of teeth or for other kinds of dental and orthodontic treatment. A mouth guard is worn inside the mouth, between the teeth, and so may only be visible when it is taken out, or the character's mouth is sufficiently [[open mouth|open]].

title: cat_eye-framed_eyewear
body:
Cat eye glasses are a shape of eyewear. The form is closely related to the browline style, differentiated by having an upsweep at the outer edges where the temples or arms join the frame front. Cat-eye glasses were popular in the 1950s and 1960s among women.  

They are somewhat teardrop shaped, but do not confuse this with [[teardrop-framed glasses]]. They are rounded towards the nose, and pointed at the eyewear's legs. They are somewhere between [[round eyewear]] and [[triangular eyewear]].

title: awacs
body: An acronym for [b]A[/b]irborne [b]W[/b]arning [b]A[/b]nd [b]C[/b]ontrol [b]S[/b]ystem. An AWACS plane is typically a modified civilian airliner with extensive electronics systems and a massive radar dish mounted to the top of the plane's fuselage. Their purpose is to coordinate the activities of large numbers of military aircraft in lieu of a traditional control tower, in addition to providing quick notice of sudden battlefield changes as well as periodically providing electronic warfare support.

title: reichsadler
body:
The [b][i]Reichsadler[/i][/b] ("Imperial Eagle") is a German [[heraldry|heraldic]] emblem used since the Holy Roman Empire as a symbol of the [[germany|German]] State, adopted by the German Empire as the national emblem. Its use as the National Emblem continued under the Weimar Republic. The Weimar version was re-adopted by the West Germany and modern-day Federal German Republic as the [i]Bundesadler[/i]. 

Despite its medieval origin, the term [i]Reichsadler[/i] in common English understanding and here refers to the [b][[Nazi]]-era[/b] version that consists of a monochrome [[eagle]] facing to its side, with straight outstretched wings, and both talons clutching a circular wreath containing a [[swastika]]. This also includes the variants, such as the [i]Parteiadler[/i] (NSDAP party emblem, left-facing) and the [[Luftwaffe]] one (curved wings with single talon clutching).

title: souryuu_(aircraft_carrier)
body:
A [[World War II]] Japanese [[aircraft carrier]] that took part in the attack on [[Pearl Harbor]].

Quoting from Conway (who spelled her as Soryu):

"[b]Soryu[/b], built under the 1931-32 Supplementary Programme, was the model for nearly all the later [[Japan]]ese carriers: fast, lightly built, and intended to deliver blows but not receive them. The flight deck was 711ft 6in x 85ft 4in, and the two hangers were served by three lifts. The small island was to starboard, and just abaft two funnels discharged almost horizontally just below flight deck level. Soryu was hit by 3 bombs from US dive-bombers in the [[Battle of Midway]], burst into flames, and blew up when the fires reached the aviation fuel tanks."

title: akagi_(aircraft_carrier)
body:
[[Aircraft carrier]] of the [[Imperial Japanese Navy]] (IJN) converted from an unfinished Amagi-class battlecruiser of same name, saw service in [[World War II]] and 2nd Sino-Japanese War. 

Served as the flagship of the First Air Fleet and led the attack on [[Pearl Harbor]] on 7 December 1941. Was sunk during the [[Battle of Midway]] with the loss of 267 men months later. 

Akagi's noticeable features were her triple flight deck set-up (feature she shared with converted Tosa-class battleship [[kaga_(aircraft_carrier)|Kaga]]) during late 20s and early 30s, and her port side island (shared with purpose built aircraft carrier Hiryu) after her modernization during mid-30s.

title: hiryuu_(aircraft_carrier)
body:
A [[World War II]] Japanese [[aircraft carrier]] that took part in the attack on [[Pearl Harbor]].

Quoting from Conway (who spelled her as Hiryu):

"[b]Hiryu[/b] (1931-32 Supplementary Programme) was a slightly enlarged and modified [[souryuu_(aircraft_carrier)|Soryu]]; the beam was increased by 1m for a 20 per cent increase in oil capacity, the protection was strengthened and the forecastle raised by a deck. The flight deck was 711ft 6in x 88ft 6in, and as in Soryu the two hangers were served by three lifts. The island was almost amidships and to port (the second and last Japanese carrier with this arrangement) where it partly balanced the two horizontally-discharging funnels to starboard. Hiryu was hit by 4 bombs from US dive-bombers in the [[Battle of Midway]], wrecking flight deck and hangers; she had to be abandoned and scuttled, the last of the 4 Japanese carriers sunk in the Battle."

title: 2_fuel_4_ammo_11_steel
body:
A nickname for [[Kantai Collection]]'s [[naka (kancolle)|Naka]]. It comes from the resources you get from dismantling her: 2 fuel, 4 ammo, and 11 steel.  Since Naka is such a common drop in battle, or the typical result of a failed attempt to create a much more impressive ship, many players will reflexively scrap her every time they get her, leading to the nickname. Although to be exact, you actually get 2-2-10 from scrapping Naka alone, if one also scraps the gun a freshly dropped or constructed Naka comes with, you get 2 ammo and 1 steel to make the 2-4-11.

It also among the first [[meme|memes]] that came about from the Kantai Collection fanbase. 

Use this tag when the specified number of objects appear in the image, or some reference to the number 2-4-11 is made. Can also be used as a generic reference to dismantling Naka, but it [i]must[/i] be Naka who is the victim; no other shipgirl qualifies for this tag.

title: taisui_xingjun_(fate)
body:
Alter Ego-class welfare Servant in [[Fate/Grand Order]]. A Chinese mythological god said to be the deified form of "Tai Sui":https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tai_Sui, a planet that mirrors Jupiter. The [[Chinese zodiac]] is based on divisions of Jupiter's orbital cycle rather than the Sun's in the Western zodiac, so Taisui is able to define whether any given year will be lucky or unlucky by using the 12 zodiac signs multiplied by the five Chinese elements (fire, earth, metal, water, and wood), or 60 divisions.

Taisui has a child form voiced by [[Minami Omi]], and an adult form voiced by [[Kawanishi Kengo]].

title: heshikiri_hasebe
body:
A [[Touken Ranbu]] character. 

The personification of the [[katana]] "of the same name":http://meitou.info/index.php/圧切. 

One of [[Oda Nobunaga]]'s favorite swords. His name comes from the incident where a servant angered his owner and hid behind a table to no avail because Oda used Hasebe to slice through the table and kill that servant. Shortly afterwards, he gave the sword to someone who wasn't even one of his trusted people. Because of that incident, Hasebe resents him. 

Hasebe is portrayed as being serious, dutiful and extremely loyal to the Saniwa, to the point that his opening lines are "If it's an order from the Master...". Artists tend to give him a comically serious personality who's utterly obsessed with pleasing the Saniwa (a trait that often comes into play in more comedic side works, such as [i]Hanamaru[/i] or the official Anthalogy; see Pool #11476 for this portrayal). He is also presented as a foil to fellow swords [[Ookurikara]] and [[Shokudaikiri Mitsutada]].

He has [[short hair|short]] [[brown hair]] and [[purple eyes]]. His standard outfit are purple [[robe]]s, [[white gloves]] and [[sode]] on each shoulder. His casual outfit is a purple and white [[track suit]]. His [[Heshikiri Hasebe (Kiwame)|Kiwame]] form has him dress similarly to a [[priest]], reflecting how his later owner, Kuroda Yoshitaka, converted to Christianity later in life.

He is featured in [i][[Touken Ranbu: Hanamaru]][/i] as one of the major supporting characters, as the [[Saniwa (touken ranbu)|]]'s secretary sword. His loyalty to the Saniwa is more exaggerated in this version. 

h4. See also

title: namazuo_toushirou
body:
A [[Touken Ranbu]] character.

A [[wakizashi]], converted from a [[naginata]]. One of the many Toushirou brothers, and is especially close to [[Honebami Toushirou]], whose quieter personality contrasts his. 

He has an outgoing, cheerful and somewhat spacey personality. His occasionally odd behavior is most notable in his Internal affairs quote "馬糞は嫌いなやつになげるー" ("I'll throw horse poop at those I hate~"), which naturally results in fanworks giving him a strange fixation on horse poop. He lost some memories due to being burned in a fire during the siege on Osaka Castle, but he claims he doesn't let his memory loss overwhelm him. However, there are indications that it bothers him more than he lets on.  

He has [[long hair|long]] [[black hair]] tied in a [[ponytail]], along with a prominent [[ahoge]], and [[purple eyes]]. His usual outfit is the [[military uniform]] worn by most of the other Awataguchi swords, along with a black [[necktie]] and black [[sode]] on one shoulder. His [[Namazuo Toushirou (Kiwame)|Kiwame]] form gives him [[high heels]] and more elaborate armor, and his hairstyle has changed to a [[high ponytail]].

Often compared to [[Shigure (kancolle)|]], with his [[black hair]] and his prominent [[ahoge]] making him look rather like a male version of her.

[i]Namazuo[/i] (鯰尾) means "[[catfish]] tail", which is reflected in his Kiwame form with the sode on his right arm resembling a catfish.

title: honebami_toushirou
body:
A [[Touken Ranbu]] character.

A [[wakizashi]] converted from a [[naginata]], and one of the many Toushirou brothers. Like [[Namazuo Toushirou]], he suffers from memory loss due to a fire (in Honebami's case, he was burned in the Great Fire of Meireki in 1657), but he has lost far more of his memories and is much more quiet and withdrawn than Namazuo is. He dislikes being touched and is not fond of interacting with any of the swords other than Namazuo, though he is fond of horses.

He has [[white hair]] (with the usual superposition with grey and silver) and he has [[purple eyes]] like Namazuo. He wears the same [[military uniform]] as most of the other Awataguchi swords, along with a black [[necktie]], [[sode]], and [[white gloves]]. His [[Honebami Toushirou (Kiwame)|Kiwame]] form gives him [[high heels]] and more elaborate armor, and his hair has grown slightly longer in the front.

[i]Honebami[/i] (骨喰) means "bone-eater", and he is sometimes depicted with [[bone|bones]] or a [[skeleton]] as his [[object namesake]]. His armor in his Kiwame form becomes somewhat skeletal in appearance to reflect this.

After his Kiwame remodel, [spoiler]he finally regains his memories. Honebami learns that he was not burned like Ichigo and Namazuo at Osaka, and it was the pain of being left behind (which ultimately saved him) when many of his brothers were burned, coupled with the fires of Meireiki burning him that caused his amnesia. After returning, he's still troubled about his memories, but he's more friendlier with the Saniwa (also revealing he doesn't dislike being touched).[/spoiler]

Voiced by Suzuki Yuuto. Artist is [[tndkworks]].

There are five of them, numbered in the order they were born:

1. blue eyes, bow behind head
2. gold eyes, bow under chin
3. blue eyes, bow under chin

When Gokotai reaches his [[Gokotai (Kiwame)|Kiwame]] form, the tiger cubs are replaced by a single adult tiger with one gold eye and one blue eye.

title: touken_ranbu
body:
[b]Touken Ranbu[/b] (刀剣乱舞, lit. "Boisterous Sword Dance", often abbreviated [i]Tourabu[/i]) is a Japanese free-to-play browser game developed by Kadokawa Games and [[Nitroplus]] released in January 2015. A mobile version of the game called [i]Touken Ranbu Pocket[/i] was released in March 2016.

The gameplay typically centers around controlling and managing [i]touken danshi[/i] (刀剣男士, lit. "sword warriors"), male personifications of historical Japanese [[sword]]s. Players assume the role of a [[saniwa_(touken_ranbu)|]] (審神者) that creates these characters in order to fight against [[jikan sokougun|monstrous]] [[kebiishi_(touken_ranbu)|enemies]] within different eras. Like in [[Kantai Collection]], battling is automated, but players can manually forge, repair, and team up their characters.

The game has two anime adaptations: one called [[Touken Ranbu: Hanamaru]] which is animated by Dogakobo and began airing in October 2016, and another, [[Katsugeki/Touken Ranbu]], animated by Ufotable which begain airing in July 2017. The game also has a series of musicals ([[Musical Touken Ranbu]]) and stage plays based on it.

title: jabulani
body:
The [[Adidas]] Jabulani is the official [[soccer_ball|match ball]] for the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]]. Jabulani means "rejoice"/"bring joy and happiness"/"to celebrate" in Zulu.

The 11 colors pay tribute to both [[soccer|soccer/football]] and the country in which Africa’s first-ever [[World Cup|FIFA World Cup]] was held, with yellow, red, and black being the stand out colors. The grip’n’groove texture were supposed to allows for maximum control, stable flight, and perfect grip under all conditions.

However, the Jabulani gained negative reception from many footballers. As the ball is designed to be "the roundest football ever made," it is too slippery to be held by goalkeepers, as well as too hard to control by players.

title: totenkopf
body:
German word for "dead man's head" ([[skull]]).

A specific form of [[skull and crossbones]] used by elite German units since the 18th century. Initially used by the cavalry. Commonly associated with the [[Nazi|Totenkopf-SS]], who used it as their [[SS insignia|emblem]] in [[World War II]]. It was also used by the armored corps and the tank crews of the [[Wehrmacht]] (who are often confused as [[Waffen-SS]] because of this and their black [[military uniform|uniforms]]). It consists of a skull without the mandible at 3/4 view over two crossbones.

body:
The [b]SIG P320[/b] is a modular striker-fired semi-automatic [b][[handgun]][/b] made by [[SIG Sauer]]. title: agent_3_(splatoon)
body:
Protagonist of [i][[splatoon_1|Splatoon]][/i]'s Hero Mode.

They are recruited into the [[squidbeak splatoon|New Squidbeak Splatoon]] by [[Cap'n Cuttlefish]] to help retrieve the [[zapfish]] from the underground civilization of Octo Valley.

Due to Agent 3 being the player character, they can be depicted as either gender, though they are often drawn as a girl with [[green_hair|green]] [[tentacle hair]] thanks to promotional materials surrounding Hero Mode. Regardless, Agent 3 always wears a "hero suit" consisting of a bright yellow safety vest and pointed [[headgear]].

By the time of [i][[Splatoon 3]][/i], they have succeeded Cuttlefish as the captain of the New Squidbeak Splatoon. In this game, they are now simply known as "Captain", while [[agent 3 (splatoon 3)|a new agent]] inherits their former "Agent 3" callsign. As the Captain, they wear the same [[blue headwear|blue]] [[peaked cap]] that Cuttlefish used to wear.

title: 8-ball
body: A solid black [[billiard ball]], the only one of this color in a standard 15-ball set composed of differently colored solid and striped balls. This ball is so distinct that it has lent its name to an entire billiards game (eight-ball, where the object is to shoot into pockets balls of one type before doing the same on the 8-ball last) and has transcended outside the context of billiards into popular culture at large. An oversized decision-making/fortune-telling device based on it called the Magic 8-Ball was invented in 1946 by Albert C. Carter and Abe Bookman and is currently manufactured by Mattel.
